            I could not possibly improve on the analysis given by the noble Lord, Lord Phillips. He is absolutely right about how paragraphs (a), (b) and (c) of subsection (4) work together. He is right that we need paragraph (c) because this is an area that will develop. We shall need those matters that are analogous to the new defined list, which is therein set out. I can reassure my noble friend that there is a good deal of jurisprudence on what "spirit" and "analogous" mean and that should
            
            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_99gc' title='Col. 99GC &mdash; HL Deb 09 February 2005 vol 669 c99GC' name='column_99gc' href='#column_99gc' rel='bookmark'>99GC</a>
